            "answer_text": "Yes. Many people think horror is about scaring the audience, but it\u2019s not. Horror is about evoking a primal emotional discomfort. Fear is one way to do that, but it isn\u2019t the only way. Horror is about finding what makes your audience anxious, what speaks to their sense of foreboding or unease, and then expressing that\u2014often through allegory or analogy. It\u2019s about creating a mood. It\u2019s about evocation. Fear is an easy way to do that (and sometimes a cheap way; jump-scares in movies make me roll my eyes). But it doesn\u2019t necessarily have to be about scaring you, even though there\u2019s often a feeling of dread that accompanies horror. Kafka\u2019s The Trial is horror, but it uses confusion and powerlessness, not fear. The Handmaid\u2019s Tale is horror that plays on themes of despair. You can paint horror with a palette of claustrophobia, angst, disillusionment, desperation, uncertainty, or dread. However you do it, horror is personal. Effective horror doesn\u2019t necessarily have to frighten your audience, but it does need to make them feel personally invested. It needs to evoke a genuine reaction. You can do that by pushing buttons we all have. Body horror pushes the button of bodily integrity, wired into our collective psyche since the days when we were prey almost as often as we were predators. The Thing and Invasion of the Body Snatchers push on fear of dissolution of the self. Alien wasn\u2019t just a monster movie; it specifically targeted sexual angst. (It\u2019s one thing to be eaten by a monster; it\u2019s another to be impregnated by one!) You can write horror if you don\u2019t get scared, but you\u2019re unlikely to write effective horror if you don\u2019t feel anything. You need to find some disquiet that you can project onto your audience. ",
