            },
            "answer_text": "I don\u2019t get scared of my own work, even though I\u2019ve been told some parts are dark and suspenseful. So, yes, you don\u2019t have to get scared to write horror. In fact, it\u2019s probably best that you don\u2019t. That way, you can analyze horror literature and learn how to write good horror stories. Much of horror is a morality play. In other words, people often get killed gruesomely because of something they\u2019ve done. Other horror \u2014 Silence of the Lambs, comes to mind, which is more of a suspense\u2014deals with the deaths of innocents and how the hero will overcome the ghastly evil. In Jaws, the skinny dipper, a child who ignored the warnings and went out too far, and Quint get killed because of their behavior. Martin Brody survives because he is the \u201cwhite knight\u201d who must slay the \u201cdragon\u201d (the great white), along with Hooper, who provides the critical information about sharks. Some horror stories have a sense of despair associated with them. The protagonist has son great sin he or she eventually atones for. The original movie, The Poseidon Adventure, is actually a horror because almost everyone dies, and even the hero must atone for challenging god. Edgar Allen Poe wrote many horrors where the protagonist has a deadly secret. So, I know this is long-winded, but you see what I\u2019m getting at. Writing horror is like writing any other genre. Read a lot of good horror and analyze why it is good. Watch decent horror movies (not necessarily slasher films, unless you really want to write that) and analyze why the story works. Good luck! ",
